Note:
This file implements TIER IDENTITY for the Runa runtime five-tier memory
model.

TIER IDENTITY - Canonical Tier Numbering and Name Lookup
- Process the canonical 5-tier numeric identifiers exposed to diagnostics,
  profilers, and any caller that needs to reason about which tier owns a
  particular pointer.
- Process tier-id-to-human-readable-name lookup for debug output and
  logging.

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- The five-tier memory model documented in docs/dev/MEMORY_ARCHITECTURE.md
  is the architectural foundation of Runa's memory subsystem; the
  numeric identifiers for each tier need a single canonical home so that
  all subsystems (arena, owned heap, ARC, page allocator, diagnostics)
  agree on what TIER 2 means.
- Name lookup is a diagnostic concern, not a runtime hot path; isolating
  it here keeps the formatting noise out of the allocators themselves.

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- MEMORY_TIER_* constants (5 of them: STACK, ARENA, OWNED, SHARED, ARC)
- get_tier_name (tier) -> human-readable string pointer

Migration history:
- 2026-05-18: Moved from compiler/internal/memory_utils.runa into the
  runtime tree per the CEO-ratified "memory management lives in runtime/
  core/memory/" ruling. The pre-migration source used a static_string
  helper wrapper around each returned literal; that wrapper had body
  `Return str` and was a one-line passthrough with zero external callers.
  The migration inlines the literal-returning behaviour into get_tier_name
  directly per the plan's recommendation, dropping the passthrough.

Dependencies:
- This file has no external runtime dependencies. Tier constants are
  pure values and the name lookup returns string literals whose addresses
  the code generator resolves at compile time.
:End Note

Note:
============================================================================
Tier Identity Constants (5-Tier Memory Architecture)
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
Runa's five-tier memory model is documented in detail in docs/dev/
MEMORY_ARCHITECTURE.md. The numeric IDs assigned here are the canonical
values; do not redefine them elsewhere.

  TIER 1 STACK   - Fastest, zero-cost, automatic (compiler-managed)
  TIER 2 ARENA   - Fast bulk, O(1) cleanup, operation-scoped temps
  TIER 3 OWNED   - Structured lifetime, deterministic, permanent data
  TIER 4 SHARED  - Manual reference counting, explicit retain/release
  TIER 5 ARC     - Automatic reference counting, compiler-inserted ref ops

The numbering starts at 1 (not 0) so that 0 can serve as the "no tier"
sentinel for callers that want to report "this pointer is not from a
tracked tier" without ambiguity.
:End Note

Constant MEMORY_TIER_STACK as Integer is 1
Constant MEMORY_TIER_ARENA as Integer is 2
Constant MEMORY_TIER_OWNED as Integer is 3
Constant MEMORY_TIER_SHARED as Integer is 4
Constant MEMORY_TIER_ARC as Integer is 5

Note:
============================================================================
Tier Name Lookup
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "get_tier_name" takes tier as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning:
        Translate a tier numeric identifier into a human-readable name for
        diagnostic dumps, profiler output, and debug logging. Returns the
        ASCII upper-case spelling that matches the constants above. An
        unrecognised tier id maps to "UNKNOWN" so that downstream
        formatters never need to special-case an integer-out-of-range
        case; they always get a printable string back.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Compare tier against each of the five canonical IDs in
               order. The order is the natural numeric order, which is
               also the most-frequent-first order for typical diagnostic
               output (STACK and ARENA dominate; SHARED and ARC are
               relatively rare in non-application code).
            2. On match, return the string literal directly. The Runa
               code generator places string literals in the .rodata
               section and the return value is a pointer to that
               read-only memory; the lifetime is the program's lifetime.
            3. On no match, fall through to "UNKNOWN" so the caller
               always receives a usable pointer.

        Migration note (2026-05-18): the pre-migration source went
        through a static_string(literal) wrapper whose body was
        `Return str`. That wrapper had no external callers and existed
        only to give the original author a place to hang a comment
        about .rodata placement. Inlining the literal returns here
        flattens the call chain and removes the wrapper Process entirely;
        the .rodata-placement comment is preserved in this annotation
        block where it belongs.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Five integer comparisons in the worst case (UNKNOWN). The compiler
        can lower this to a jump table or a sequence of compare-and-
        return; either way it is constant-time and on the order of
        nanoseconds per call. Diagnostic-only use; never put this on the
        allocation hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The returned pointer is to a .rodata literal. Writing through it
        will fault on every platform Runa supports. Callers must not
        attempt to mutate the returned string; if a mutable copy is
        needed, duplicate via arena_string_duplicate first.
    @End Security_Scope

    If tier is equal to MEMORY_TIER_STACK:
        Return "STACK"
    End If

    If tier is equal to MEMORY_TIER_ARENA:
        Return "ARENA"
    End If

    If tier is equal to MEMORY_TIER_OWNED:
        Return "OWNED"
    End If

    If tier is equal to MEMORY_TIER_SHARED:
        Return "SHARED"
    End If

    If tier is equal to MEMORY_TIER_ARC:
        Return "ARC"
    End If

    Return "UNKNOWN"
End Process
